@Julian  you're right, by trim out the _dump_str, my unicode worked.
```
def _dump_str(v):
    return v
```

This sounds great!  For most of the templating I do I'd be able to use this method, and just use fusesoc_generators when the templates need access to the generic parameters of the module.

Another thing that might be nice to add is macro elaboration.

As an example, I often have a pipeline register that is actived using a generic parameter.

```
yes_use_register: if USE_THIS_REGISTER = '1' generate
    process(clk)
    begin
        if rising_edge(clk) then
            if reset = '1' then
                b_valid <= '0';
            else
                b_valid <= a_valid;
            end if;
            b_data <= a_data;
            b_blah <= a_blah;
       end if;
     end process;
end generate;

no_use_register: if USE_THIS_REGISTER = '0' generate
    a_valid <= b_valid;
    a_data <= b_data;
    a_blah <= b_blah;
end generate;
```

It's obviously tedious and bug prone to write this out all the time, and instantiating an entity doesn't work since the elements in the data flow ('data' and 'blah' in this example) will vary.  Instead I just use a macro.

```
@@ DATA_BUFFER USE_THIS_REGISTER reset a_ b_ data blah @@
```

which can be elaborated to give the above code.  Because VHDL does not support macros like this natively I expand the macro using a python function with fusesoc_generators.  It would be cool if I could define macros like this using fusesoc directly.

@MrYsLab Sorry, there are something wrong in my last test....Ignore that (adding sleep to 100 will fail to detect board, not sure why it passed yesterday! maybe because I am too sleepy and something with my eye!!!).

I've carefully tested today, and I do find an issue in your master code for the fix, in "pymata_command_handler.py", the sleep is inside "if" part, you need to move it out of "if" and make it parallel with "if" statement, which seems like a minor mistake when you submit the code.
With this correct sleep adde, it do resolve the issue (I originally thought sleep(.1) means sleep 0.1ms so get the conclusion that it should not resolve it, but in fact it is 100ms, and I agree it can lower the CPU usage now)

From (your current code):
```python
while not self.is_stopped():
            if len(self.pymata.command_deque):
                 ...other code....
                else:
                    time.sleep(.01)
```

To:
```python
while not self.is_stopped():
            if len(self.pymata.command_deque):
                  ...other code....
            else:
                time.sleep(.01)
```

Also, if I change both 2 sleep in pymata_serial.py and pymata_command_handler.py to 0.001s, the CPU load is about 10% to 15% only (Note: just the simple code, no analog reporting, but I guess even with reporting, the load will not be higher as the sleep is still there). For people who need a little higher real-time, using 0.001s may be enough. Or, use 0.01s or 0.1s accordingly (less than 2% CPU in my system).

Hope it is helpful for other users reading this thread.

Thanks,
Shenghong

