Original comment by: Hárísh Bárvékár

Hi Rich, just wanted to give you a quick update. I have been debugging your scenario. I found a couple of bugs I will be fixing:

1. The inference event cleanup routine is not kicking in, so the inference event list grows on every timeout, the inference evaluation time degrades and as a consequence it takes longer to fire the flowchart actions.
2. There is a sig 11 in the LRU cache implementation in the client, if you try to increase the number of sids beyond 1024, the client process will crash.

This slightly simpler ruleset doesn't trigger the cleanup problem, you can try it while I fix the problems above:

```javascript
  var sidCount = 1024;
  var counters = new Array(sidCount).fill(0);
  var side = Math.ceil(Math.sqrt(sidCount));
  function printCounters() {
    for(var i = 0; i < side; i++) {
      var start = i * side;
      process.stdout.write('|' + counters.slice(start, start + side - 1).join(' ') + '|\n');
    }
  }

  with(d.ruleset('test')) {
    whenAll(m.command.eq('start').or(timeout('timeout')), function(c) {
        c.s.count = (c.s.count ? c.s.count + 1: 1);
        counters[c.s.sid] = c.s.count;
        if(c.s.sid === 0) {
          console.log(Date() + ': Fired action for sid[' + c.s.sid + ']');
          printCounters();
        }
        c.startTimer('timeout', 1, 't_' + c.s.count);
    });
    whenStart(function (host) {
      for(var i = 0; i < sidCount; i++) {
        host.post('test', {id: sidCount, sid: i, command: 'start'});
      }
    });
  }   

  d.runAll();
```

In your scenario as you add more SIDs, you will reach a point where the system won't be able to evaluate all the events under 1 second. The first gate will be redis, you can scale redis by adding more instances (passing several db objects in the runAll function). The second gate will be the number of client processes, you can scale the clients by using the 'cluster' module.

