Hiya! Thanks for that, nice recipe. I think you could also do this without rebuilding `walk()` by calling `os.walk()` and doing the limit by modifying `dirs` during the walk (per the documentation). For example, this function from [this StackOverflow answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/234329) does that. And I've added a couple of lines (untested code) to filter `files` with a regex too:

    def walklevel(some_dir, level=1, regex=None):
        some_dir = some_dir.rstrip(os.path.sep)
        assert os.path.isdir(some_dir)
        num_sep = some_dir.count(os.path.sep)
        for root, dirs, files in os.walk(some_dir):
            if regex:
                files = [f for f in files if re.match(regex, f)]
            yield root, dirs, files
            num_sep_this = root.count(os.path.sep)
            if num_sep + level <= num_sep_this:
                del dirs[:]

```
