@sgillies I merged the round trip tests but eventually dropped all but RGB ones. The reason is that it's very difficult to know if a color is even valid in other colorspaces; similar to GDAL's approach to catching invalid coordinate projections, the only way you can really find out if an arbitrary color coordinate is valid is to try to round trip it. Catch-22 for testing since we can't assume our parameterized matrix of colors contains valid colors that can be converted through any arbitrary color space.

RGB colors represent the most limited subset of the color space so we *can* assume that they are invertable. So I left that test. Since almost all geo data starts and ends in RGB spaces, it's also the most practical test.

I added `colormath` as a test dependency to a) test our fixtures and b) as a fallback to double-check for  uninvertable coords. Ideally I'd like to fill that out with a suite of manual fixtures that can be confirmed against other sources. For now, I'm happy with the results.

